      "correctIndex": 1,
      "misconceptionFeedback": "⚠️ Common misconception! Many students think heavier = faster falling. In a vacuum, all objects fall with the same gravitational acceleration (g = 9.8 m/s²) regardless of mass. The confusion comes from air resistance in everyday life - not gravity itself.",
      "correctFeedback": "✓ Correct! In a vacuum, mass doesn’t affect free fall. All objects accelerate at g = 9.8 m/s² - Galileo demonstrated this. Everyday confusion comes from air resistance, not gravity.",
